[2025-12-27 16:32:56] ðŸ’¡ AI DECISION: One small, valid web UI improvement would be to enhance the responsiveness of the loading animation by adding inertia to it. 

Currently, the loading animation scales up and down without any easing, creating an unpleasant jerkiness. By adding a cubic-bezier easing function, the animation will become smoother and more visually appealing.

Here's the modified `style.css` code:

```css
#loading-page .loading {
  position: fixed;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  z-index: 100;
  width: 100px;
  height: 100px;
  border-radius: 50%;
  background-color: #000;
  animation: loading-animation 2s cubic-bezier(0.25, 0.1, 0.25, 1); /* add this */
}

#loading-page.hide-loading {
  animation: none;
}

@keyframes loading-animation {
  0% {
    transform: scale(0.5);
  }
  50% {
    transform: scale(1);
  }
  100% {
    transform: scale(0.5);
  }
}
```

Alternatively, you can use other easing functions like `ease-in`, `ease-out`, `ease-in-out`, `cubic-bezier(0, 0, 1, 1)`, etc., depending on your design requirements.

This change will enhance the loading animation experience and provide a more cohesive user interface.
