[2025-12-27 16:34:00] ðŸ’¡ AI DECISION: One small, valid web UI improvement is to add a loading animation to the navigation menu when the page is loading. This will improve the user experience by giving the user a visual cue that the page is still being loaded.

To implement this, you can add a CSS class to the navigation menu that shows the loading animation when the page is loaded. You can use the CSS class `.loading` and `.hide-loading` from your existing style.css file.

Here's the updated code for the navigation menu (in games.html):

```html
<div class="topnav">
  <!-- ...
</div>

<div class="loading">
  <!-- ...
</div>

<script>
  // Wait for the page to be loaded
  window.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    // Remove the loading animation when the page is loaded
    document.body.classList.remove('loading');
  });
</script>
```

You can also add some animation to the loading animation to make it more visually appealing. For example, you can add a fade-in or fade-out animation to the loading text.

Here's an updated version of the loading animation CSS class (in style.css):

```css
.loading {
  position: fixed;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  z-index: 100;
  width: 100px;
  height: 100px;
  border-radius: 50%;
  background-color: #000;
  opacity: 0;
  transition: opacity 2s;
}

.loading.show {
  opacity: 1;
}

.loading.hide {
  opacity: 0;
  animation: fade-out 2s;
}

@keyframes fade-out {
  0% {
    opacity: 1;
  }
  100% {
    opacity: 0;
  }
}
```

And here's the updated JavaScript code for the loading animation:

```javascript
<script>
  // Wait for the page to be loaded
  window.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    // Remove the loading animation when the page is loaded
    document.body.classList.remove('loading');
  });
  
  document.body.classList.add('loading');
</script>
```

This will add a fading effect to the loading animation when the page is loaded. The `.loading` class still controls the position and size of the loading animation, but the opacity of the animation will fade in and out.
